{
  "id": "ch9",
  "course": "Katzung Pharmacology",
  "chapter": 9,
  "title": "Adrenoceptor Agonists & Sympathomimetic Drugs",
  "subtitle": "High-Yield Summary",
  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "1-high-yield-summary",
      "number": 1,
      "title": "High-Yield Summary",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Sympathomimetic drugs mimic sympathetic nervous system activity.",
            "They act by:",
            "Direct receptor activation: epinephrine, norepinephrine, phenylephrine, dobutamine.",
            "Indirect catecholamine enhancement: amphetamine, tyramine, cocaine.",
            "Mixed action: ephedrine.",
            "Main receptors: alpha1, alpha2, beta1, beta2, beta3, D1, D2.",
            "Clinical themes:",
            "alpha1 = vasoconstriction.",
            "alpha2 = decreased sympathetic outflow.",
            "beta1 = cardiac stimulation.",
            "beta2 = bronchodilation and smooth muscle relaxation.",
            "beta3 = bladder relaxation.",
            "D1 = renal/splanchnic vasodilation."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_9/02-table-9-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 9-1 — Adrenoceptor types and subtypes"
    },
    {
      "id": "2-core-concepts",
      "number": 2,
      "title": "Core Concepts",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Adrenergic Receptors"
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            "Receptor",
            "G protein",
            "Main signaling",
            "Key effects"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "alpha1",
              "Gq",
              "↑ IP3/DAG, ↑ Ca2+",
              "Vasoconstriction, mydriasis, urinary retention"
            ],
            [
              "alpha2",
              "Gi",
              "↓ cAMP",
              "↓ NE release, ↓ sympathetic outflow"
            ],
            [
              "beta1",
              "Gs",
              "↑ cAMP",
              "↑ HR, ↑ contractility, ↑ renin"
            ],
            [
              "beta2",
              "Gs",
              "↑ cAMP",
              "Bronchodilation, vasodilation, uterine relaxation, ↑ K+ uptake"
            ],
            [
              "beta3",
              "Gs",
              "↑ cAMP",
              "Bladder detrusor relaxation, lipolysis"
            ],
            [
              "D1",
              "Gs",
              "↑ cAMP",
              "Renal/splanchnic vasodilation"
            ],
            [
              "D2",
              "Gi",
              "↓ cAMP",
              "↓ transmitter release"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_9/06-table-9-3.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 9-3 — Distribution of adrenoceptor subtypes",
      "imageSupplement": "data_9/02-table-9-1.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "TABLE 9-1 — Adrenoceptor G proteins & effects"
    },
    {
      "id": "3-key-mechanisms-pathways",
      "number": 3,
      "title": "Key Mechanisms / Pathways",
      "layout": "center",
      "reveal": "up",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "alpha1 pathway"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha1 → Gq → phospholipase C → IP3/DAG → ↑ intracellular Ca2+",
            "Result: smooth muscle contraction.",
            "Important sites: vascular smooth muscle, pupil dilator, bladder sphincter/prostate."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "alpha2 pathway"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 → Gi → ↓ adenylyl cyclase → ↓ cAMP.",
            "Presynaptic alpha2 decreases norepinephrine release.",
            "CNS alpha2 agonists decrease sympathetic outflow."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "beta pathway"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "beta1/beta2/beta3 → Gs → ↑ adenylyl cyclase → ↑ cAMP.",
            "beta1 in heart: ↑ Ca2+ influx → ↑ heart rate and contractility.",
            "beta2 in smooth muscle: relaxation.",
            "beta3 in bladder: detrusor relaxation."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Dopamine pathway"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "D1 → Gs → vasodilation, especially renal/splanchnic vessels.",
            "D2 → Gi → decreased neurotransmitter release."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_9/01-fig-9-1.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 9-1 — Activation of α₁ responses",
      "imageSupplement": "data_9/03-fig-9-2.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "FIGURE 9-2 — Adenylyl cyclase (β & α₂)"
    },
    {
      "id": "4-important-drugs-molecules-systems",
      "number": 4,
      "title": "Important Drugs / Molecules / Systems",
      "layout": "left",
      "reveal": "left",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Epinephrine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Receptors: alpha1, alpha2, beta1, beta2.",
            "Effects:",
            "↑ systolic BP from beta1 cardiac stimulation.",
            "↓ diastolic BP at low doses due to beta2 vasodilation.",
            "Bronchodilation via beta2.",
            "Vasoconstriction via alpha1.",
            "Uses:",
            "Anaphylaxis.",
            "Cardiac arrest.",
            "Added to local anesthetics to prolong action.",
            "Exam pearl: best drug for anaphylaxis because it treats airway, vascular collapse, and bronchospasm."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Norepinephrine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Receptors: alpha1, alpha2, beta1.",
            "Minimal beta2 activity.",
            "Effects:",
            "Strong vasoconstriction.",
            "↑ systolic and diastolic BP.",
            "Reflex bradycardia may occur.",
            "Use: septic shock / severe hypotension.",
            "Exam pearl: strong pressor with reflex bradycardia."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Dopamine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Traditional dose-dependent exam pattern:",
            "Low dose: D1 → renal/splanchnic vasodilation.",
            "Moderate dose: beta1 → ↑ contractility.",
            "High dose: alpha1 → vasoconstriction.",
            "Use: selected shock states historically; norepinephrine is generally preferred in septic shock because dopamine causes more arrhythmias."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Phenylephrine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Selective alpha1 agonist.",
            "Effects:",
            "Vasoconstriction.",
            "↑ BP.",
            "Reflex bradycardia.",
            "Mydriasis without cycloplegia.",
            "Uses:",
            "Nasal decongestant.",
            "Mydriatic.",
            "Hypotension.",
            "Toxicity: hypertension, reflex bradycardia."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Midodrine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Oral prodrug → desglymidodrine.",
            "Selective alpha1 agonist.",
            "Use: orthostatic hypotension.",
            "Toxicity:",
            "Supine hypertension.",
            "Piloerection.",
            "Urinary retention.",
            "Exam pearl: used in autonomic failure but can worsen urinary retention."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Clonidine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 agonist.",
            "Mechanism: decreases CNS sympathetic outflow.",
            "Uses:",
            "Hypertension.",
            "ADHD.",
            "Withdrawal syndromes.",
            "Toxicity:",
            "Sedation.",
            "Dry mouth.",
            "Bradycardia.",
            "Rebound hypertension if stopped suddenly."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Methyldopa"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 agonist.",
            "Use: hypertension in pregnancy.",
            "Toxicity: sedation, hemolytic anemia, hyperprolactinemia."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Dexmedetomidine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 agonist.",
            "Use: ICU/procedural sedation.",
            "Benefit: sedation with less respiratory depression."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Tizanidine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 agonist.",
            "Use: muscle spasticity.",
            "Pitfall: can cause hypotension and rebound hypertension."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Brimonidine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha2 agonist.",
            "Mechanism: reduces aqueous humor production and increases uveoscleral outflow.",
            "Use: open-angle glaucoma (topical eye drops).",
            "Advantage: does not affect pupil size or accommodation — useful when miosis or cycloplegia must be avoided.",
            "Toxicity: local allergy, ocular hyperemia; systemic absorption may cause sedation and hypotension."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Dobutamine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Predominantly beta1 agonist.",
            "Effects:",
            "↑ contractility more than ↑ HR.",
            "Increases cardiac output.",
            "Uses:",
            "Acute heart failure.",
            "Cardiogenic shock.",
            "Pharmacologic cardiac stress testing.",
            "Toxicity: tachyarrhythmias, increased myocardial oxygen demand."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Isoproterenol"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Nonselective beta1 + beta2 agonist.",
            "Effects:",
            "Marked tachycardia.",
            "↓ diastolic BP from beta2 vasodilation.",
            "Rarely used clinically."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Albuterol / Terbutaline"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "beta2 agonists.",
            "Effects:",
            "Bronchodilation.",
            "Uterine relaxation.",
            "Drives K+ into cells.",
            "Uses:",
            "Asthma/COPD.",
            "Hyperkalemia adjunct.",
            "Toxicity:",
            "Tremor.",
            "Tachycardia.",
            "Hypokalemia."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Mirabegron"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "beta3 agonist.",
            "Effect: relaxes detrusor muscle.",
            "Use: overactive bladder.",
            "Toxicity: hypertension."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Fenoldopam"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "D1 agonist.",
            "Effect: renal and systemic vasodilation.",
            "Use: hypertensive emergency.",
            "Toxicity: hypotension, tachycardia, headache."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Amphetamine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Indirect sympathomimetic.",
            "Mechanism: releases norepinephrine and dopamine.",
            "Uses:",
            "ADHD.",
            "Narcolepsy.",
            "Toxicity:",
            "Insomnia.",
            "Appetite suppression.",
            "Hypertension.",
            "Dependence/abuse."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Tyramine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Indirect sympathomimetic found in aged cheese, cured meats, fermented foods.",
            "Normally metabolized by MAO.",
            "With MAO inhibitors → hypertensive crisis.",
            "Exam pearl: MAOI + tyramine = severe hypertension."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Cocaine"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Blocks reuptake of norepinephrine, dopamine, serotonin.",
            "Effects:",
            "Sympathetic stimulation.",
            "Vasoconstriction.",
            "CNS stimulation.",
            "Toxicity:",
            "Hypertension.",
            "Coronary vasospasm.",
            "MI.",
            "Arrhythmias.",
            "Seizures."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Metaraminol"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Mixed-acting sympathomimetic (similar to ephedrine).",
            "Mechanism: direct alpha1 receptor stimulation + indirect norepinephrine release from nerve terminals.",
            "Effects: vasoconstriction and increased blood pressure; reflex bradycardia at higher doses.",
            "Use: acute hypotension (e.g., spinal anesthesia-induced hypotension).",
            "Advantage over ephedrine: longer duration; less beta1 cardiac stimulation.",
            "Toxicity: hypertension, reflex bradycardia, reduced cardiac output.",
            "Note: tachyphylaxis can occur with repeated doses due to depletion of NE stores."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_9/04-table-9-2.png",
      "imageCaption": "TABLE 9-2 — Relative receptor affinities",
      "imageSupplement": "data_9/07-fig-9-4.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "FIGURE 9-4 — Catecholamine structures"
    },
    {
      "id": "5-clinical-correlations",
      "number": 5,
      "title": "Clinical Correlations",
      "layout": "right",
      "reveal": "right",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Orthostatic hypotension in autonomic failure"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Failure of sympathetic compensation when standing.",
            "Findings:",
            "Large BP drop on standing.",
            "Inadequate HR increase.",
            "Low plasma norepinephrine.",
            "Treatment:",
            "Midodrine.",
            "Droxidopa.",
            "Avoid:",
            "alpha blockers such as tamsulosin.",
            "unnecessary vasodilators.",
            "Important: patients are hypersensitive to pressor drugs."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Anaphylaxis"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Drug of choice: intramuscular epinephrine.",
            "Mechanisms:",
            "alpha1: vasoconstriction, reduces edema, increases BP.",
            "beta1: increases cardiac output.",
            "beta2: bronchodilation, reduces mediator release."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Shock"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Preferred vasopressor in septic shock: norepinephrine.",
            "Dobutamine may be added when low cardiac output is present."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Nasal congestion"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "alpha1 agonists constrict nasal mucosal vessels.",
            "Drugs: phenylephrine, oxymetazoline, pseudoephedrine.",
            "Pitfall: topical overuse → rebound congestion / rhinitis medicamentosa."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Asthma/COPD"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "beta2 agonists cause bronchodilation.",
            "Short acting: albuterol.",
            "Long acting: salmeterol, formoterol.",
            "Ultra-long acting in COPD: indacaterol, olodaterol, vilanterol."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "content": "Horner syndrome pharmacology"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "Postganglionic lesion: indirect agonists fail because catecholamine stores are lost.",
            "Direct agonists such as phenylephrine still dilate the pupil."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "image": "data_9/11-fig-9-6.png",
      "imageCaption": "FIGURE 9-6 — Hemodynamic effects of sympathomimetics",
      "imageSupplement": "data_9/09-fig-9-5.png",
      "imageSupplementCaption": "FIGURE 9-5 — Noncatecholamine sympathomimetics"
    },
